# Digital Communication Gone Wrong
In 2013, a PR professional named Justine Sacco tweeted a joke before boarding a long-haul flight to South Africa. By the time she landed with her phone off the tweet had gone viral, trending worldwide under a hashtag mocking her. She had lost her job before she even stepped off the plane.
What made the situation worse was the lack of context and the speed of social media  a single poorly worded post reached thousands of people in minutes, with no opportunity for her to clarify or apologise in real time.
What could have been done differently is simple: pausing before posting. Asking "could this be misread?" or "does this need context?" takes seconds. Enabling notifications and checking responses before going offline could also have allowed for an early correction before the situation spiralled.
